"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by COSLA&#xa0;Executive Summary&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Introduction&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nReplacement of Housing Benefit by Universal Credit &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nUnder Occupancy changes&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAll \nScottish \ncouncils with housing stock \n(26 out of 32) \na\nre seeing an increase in rent arrears.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThree quarters attribute this to under occupancy deductions in housing benefit.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFour out of five councils \nwere\n receiving ha\nlf or less of the additional rent now due from tenants\n at the end of May\n; three out of five councils \nwere\n receiving 40% or less of the missing revenue.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe July follow up \nsample \nsurvey confirmed that rent arrears were continuing to increase for councils a\nt the end of the first quarter of 2013/14.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe \nScottish \npicture of limited \nsmaller size stock \navailability was confirmed in \nthis\n recent sample of councils, meaning that, for the vast majority of tenants affecte\nd by under occupancy deductions\n, there is no \nreal prospect of a move to avoid th\nis \nreduction in \nthe near future.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThere has been a massive demand for Discretionary Housing Payments – 22,000 at end of May (4 times the rate experienced last year for most councils).\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n44% \nof applicants were awarded DH\nPs at that point.\n  By the end of May 22% of the £10m Scottish allocatio\nn for DHP was already committed.\n&#xa0;\n•\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMost councils are seeing an impact on their temporary accommodation – current feedback suggests they are estimating a £0.75m loss from under occupancy.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nend of year \nincreases in rent arrears over the 2012/2013 \nfigure\n (One council did not provide a response and another could not provide an accurate figure)\n. These showed substantial increases in gross rent arrears at financial year end from the position at the end of the June quarter. These projected gross rent arrear i\nncreases, from 2012/13, for all 4 councils total £3.9m at year end, with projections varying from gross increases of £237k to £1.9m.  \nCOSLA is projecting an additional £15m in rent arrears to \nScottish \ncouncils from under occupancy (bedroom tax) at year end.  The RSL sector has nearly as much housing stock and anecdotal feedback suggests that additional arrears in that sector are also likely to be substantial. Feedback to COSLA suggests \nc\n£6\n to £10\nm \nfrom \ncouncils \nalready invested in additional local supports\n.\n Councils have \nalso \nalready added around £3m to the DWP allocation and we expect this figure to double. \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nDirect Payments &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHomelessness Prevention&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSupported Accommodation&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nConclusion              \n \n27 September 2013&#xa0;\n"